<br>
I was going to post this on the submission thread, but since it has nothing to do with that topic, I thought I'd start a new one here.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I am still left wondering, if the OT law was abolished, and the NT law is all we need, and as your article points out and CEREMONIAL law is worthless, how does this reconcile with the first 3 commandments since they are all ceremonial as well? The answer that I think I know is that you selectively apply the bible to your life.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I didn't read the entire article that Heather posted ... so I cannot comment on ceremonial law, etc. But I posted the beginning of this earlier on the JS thread to explain the abolishment of food restrictions (shellfish, pork, etc). I'll also add about abstaining from sex. First the food:<br>
<br>
In Acts, chapter 10, Peter has a vision while on a roof top praying. &quot; ... he fell into a trance adn saw heaven opened and an object like a great sheet bound at four corners, descending to him and let down to the earth. In it were all kinds of four-footed animals of the earth, wild beasts, creeping things, and birds of the air. And a voice came to him, 'Rise, Peter; kill and eat.' But Peter said, 'Not so, Lord! For I have never eaten anything common or unclean.' And a voice spoke to him again the second time, 'What God has cleansed you must not call common.' This was done three times. And the object was taken up into heaven again.&quot; (Acts 10:11-16) God was telling Peter that these foods that had once been unclean were now alright to eat of; He was also telling Peter that it was alright to keep company with Gentiles, who were also viewed as &quot;unclean&quot; by devout Jews. Later, in the book of Romans, Paul addresses this issue as well. &quot;Do not destroy the work of God for the sake of food. All things indeed are pure, but it is evil for the man who eats with offense. It is good neither to eat meat nor drink wine nor do anything by which your brother stumbles or is offended or is made weak.&quot; (Romans 14:19-21) Basically, Paul is reaffirming that food is no longer seen as &quot;unclean,&quot; but the person eating or drinking needs to take into account those they are with - if their food or drink will offend or cause another to stumble, then it is best to abstain while dining with that person. And finally, from the Man Himself: &quot;He said to them, 'Hear and understand: 'Not what goes into the mouth defiles a man; but what comes out of him mouth, this defiles a man.'&quot; (Matthew 15:11) Jesus was telling the Jews of His day that it is not the food that makes them unclean, but rather their words, and if you read further, their hearts that make them unclean. <br>
<br>
Okay, sex: Paul writes in 1 Corintians 7: &quot;Nevertheless, because of sexual immorality, let each man have his own wife, and let each woman have her own husband. Let the husband render to his wife the affection due her, and likewise, also the wife to her husband. ... Do not deprive one another except with consent for a time, that you may give yourselves to fasting and prayer; and come together again so that Satan does not tempt you because of your lack of self-control. But I say this as a concession, not as a commandment.&quot; (vs. 2-3, 5-6) Husbands and wifes are to give themselves to each other, including sexually. Instead of falling into temptation (lust, sexual immorality, pornography, etc), if spouses would be attuned to the sexual needs of their partner, and lovingly &amp; willingly satisfy each other's sexual needs, then they can withstand any temptation to sin. <br>
<br>
Both of these restrictions, from the OT times, were given by God to prevent His people from falling victim to illness and disease. Many of the &quot;commands&quot; given in the OT were to direct the Israelites towards healthy and righteous living. They would be considered proper conduct for living a life pleasing to God. The Ten Commandments still hold to this day - which as Jesus stated, can be summed up into two commandments: Love the Lord your God with all your heart, mind, and soul; and love your neighbor as yourself. If you do those two things, then the others fall into place. Jesus' life exemplified those two commands and we are to follow His example. You are right; there are many &quot;regulations&quot; that fall into the category of &quot;law&quot; in the Bible that most all Christians today do not worry with nor practice. As pointed out, some have been redefined by God; others, we don't practice from chioce. Does this mean a person who has accepted Christ, His death, His atonement, and His resurrection will not be saved? No. Our salvation does not have to do with whether we wear clothing of blended thread (which if you look at that in a practical sense, clothing made of blended thread will wear out unevenly, wasting the thread and the garment). Our salvation rests on Christ alone. The church in Galatia was having a very hard time trying to keep the Law, believing that deviating from it would affect their salvation. Paul writes to them: &quot;Is the law then against the promises of God? Certainly not! For if there had been a law given which could have given eternal life, truly righteousness would have been by the law. But the Scripture has confined all under sin, that the promise by faith in Jesus Christ might be given to those who believe. But before faith came, we were kept nder guard by the law, kept for the faith which would afterward be revealed. Therefore the law was our tutor to bring us to Christ, that we might be justified by faith. But after faith has come, we are not longer under a tutor.&quot; (Galatians 3:21-25) Paul points out elsewhere in his letters that the Law served to show us our sin and show us the need for a Savior. Think about it - who could ever fulfill all of the laws, regulations and commands of the OT? None of us. The law, then, shows us our shortcomings and impresses upon us the need for someone else to get us back to righteousness and holiness. The someone is Christ. We trust in Christ to be our salvation and then try our darndest to keep His commands - summed up by the two greatest - Love God and love our neighbor as ourself. <br>
<br>
I am sorry this has gotten a little long. Hopefully it will help you see our perspective - not expecting you to agree or accept any of it. I agree with Heather (I think she posted it) that people who are not of God cannot understand the things of God - you must be able to step out on faith first in Him befoe any of the rest of it makes a hill of beans.<br>
<br>
