<br>
In the sacrificial lamb, it had to be the first born, it had to be without blemish, the blood was shed so that the persons sins could be atoned for.  These are all symbols of Jesus Christ.<br>
<br>
Circumcision was a symbol of being a separate, unique covenant people. It was also a symbol of humility and submission to God <br>
<br>
Dueteronomy 10:16<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>16 Circumcise therefore the foreskin of your heart, and be no more stiffnecked<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The food laws were symbolic of keeping yourself clean and unspotted from the influence of the gentiles or the eveil in the world. <br>
<br>
All of things pointed to the Atonement.  The fufillment of the laws.  The laws were given to teach and prepare the people for the arrival of the Messiah and the Atonement. In Christs completion of the atonement, no more need to prepare for it.(the laws)<br>
<br>
The Gospel and the sacrafice of God was the new covenant  see Hebrew 8, 9 and 10.  And in completing the final sacrafice did not destroy the law in the sense that the law was without merit, but fufilled or a better word would be completed the law.<br>
<br>
I have been trying to think of an example and the best I can come up with is comparing the Mosaic law to rehearsals for a play. You practice and practice and practice and then comes the real thing. The presentation of the Play.  In performing the play, you dont destroy the rehearsals, you complete or fufill them.  And after the play is performed, there is no reason to continue rehearsing.<br>
<br>
An example of higher law would be while your children are young you have a set bedtime which you enforce.  The principle/value for the bedtime is that the child needs sufficient rest.  As the child grows in their understanding, instead of strictly enforcing a bedtime, you teach them the principle, rest is good for you.  <br>
